{
  "texts": [
    "Its obligations aim to compel platforms to take a more responsible approach to content moderation and transparency.The DSA was proposed by the European Commission in December 2020 alongside the Digital Markets Act [59], as part of a comprehensive approach to regulating digital services and promoting online safety.",
    "Following political agreement between EU co-legislators, it entered into force on 16 November 2022.The DSA introduced a phased rollout of obligations to provide platforms time to adapt.",
    "By 17 February 2023, online intermediaries had to report active EU user numbers to determine qualification as VLOPs or VLOSEs.On 25 April 2023, the Commission formally designated 17 VLOPs and 2 VLOSEs reaching over 45 million monthly EU users [51].",
    "These entities had 4 months to fully comply with extensive DSA obligations around risk assessments, independent auditing, transparency reporting, content moderation, advertising rules, and due diligence.By 17 February 2024, EU member states had to establish their national Digital Services Coordinators responsible for DSA supervision and enforcement [52].",
    "This was also the deadline for all other online platforms to comply with baseline DSA rules on issues like notice-and-takedown procedures and internal complaint systems."
  ]
}